	    </section>
	    <section>
	      <title>Discussion</title>
	      <para>In the first beaker, liquid water becomes water vapour as a result of evaporation and the water level drops. A small amount of gas molecules will condense again, but because the gas molecules can escape from the system there is much less condensation than evaporation.</para>
	      <para>In the second beaker, evaporation also takes place. However, in this case, the vapour comes into contact with the surface of the glass cover and it cools and condenses to form liquid water again. This water is returned to the beaker. Once condensation has begun, the rate at which the water level drops will start to decrease. At some point, the rate of evaporation will be equal to the rate of condensation, and there will be no change in the water level in the beaker. This can be represented as follows:</para>
	      <para><emphasis effect="bold"><latex>\text{liquid} \rightleftharpoons \text{vapour}</latex></emphasis></para>
	      <para>In this example, the reaction (in this case, a change in the phase of water) can proceed in either direction. In the forward direction there is a change in phase from liquid to gas, present here as water vapour. A reverse change can also take place, when vapour condenses to form liquid again.</para>
	    </section>
	  </activity>
	  <note type="aside">
	    <para><emphasis effect="bold">Evaporation</emphasis> is when a substance goes from the liquid phase to the gas phase (it evaporates). <emphasis effect="bold">Condensation</emphasis> is when a substance goes from the gas phase to the liquid phase (it condenses).</para>
	    <para>The bottle contains water vapour (gas) and water droplets are condensing on the side of the bottle.</para>
	    <image style:width="0.25">
	      <src>photos/condensation.jpg</src>
	      <attribution>Photo by Muffet on Flickr</attribution>
	    </image>
	  </note>
	  <para>An <emphasis effect="bold">open system</emphasis> is one in which matter or energy can flow into or out of the system. In the liquid-gas demonstration we used, the first beaker was an example of an open system because the beaker could be heated or cooled (a change in <emphasis effect="italics">energy</emphasis>), and water vapour (the <emphasis effect="italics">matter</emphasis>) could evaporate from the beaker.</para>
          <definition>
            <term>Open system</term>
            <meaning>
	      <para>An <emphasis effect="italics">open system</emphasis> is one whose borders allow the movement of <emphasis effect="bold">energy and matter</emphasis> into and out of the system.</para>
            </meaning>
          </definition>
          <para>A <emphasis effect="bold">closed system</emphasis> is one in which energy can enter or leave, but matter cannot. The second beaker with the glass cover is an example of a closed system. The beaker can still be heated or cooled, but water vapour cannot leave the system because the glass cover is a barrier. Condensation changes the vapour to liquid and returns it to the beaker. In other words, there is no loss of matter from the system.</para>
	  <note type="aside">
	    <para>Generally, some of the molecules at the surface of liquids and solids are moving into the gas phase. This means that matter is leaving the system. However, this is such a small fraction of the total volume of the liquid or solid that a reaction involving only solids or liquids can be considered a closed system.</para>
	  </note>
	  <note type="aside">
	    <para>It is useful to simplify situations in science by dividing the world into the <emphasis effect="italics">system</emphasis> we are studying, and the surrounding environment that might influence the reaction, but is not part of it.</para>
	  </note>
	  <definition>
            <term>Closed system</term>
            <meaning>
	      <para>A <emphasis effect="italics">closed system</emphasis> is one in which <emphasis effect="bold">only energy</emphasis> can move into and out of the system. Matter cannot be gained by the system nor lost from the system.</para>
            </meaning>
          </definition>
        </section>
        <para>In a <emphasis effect="bold">closed system</emphasis> it is possible for reactions to be reversible, such as in the demonstration above. In a closed system, it is also possible for a chemical reaction to reach <emphasis effect="bold">equilibrium</emphasis>.</para>        <section type="subsection">
          <title>Reversible reactions</title>
          <shortcode>ESCAX</shortcode>
	  <para>Some reactions can take place in two directions. In one direction the reactants combine to form the products. This is called the <emphasis effect="bold"><latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward reaction}}</latex></emphasis>. In the other direction, the products react to form the reactants again. This is called the <emphasis effect="bold"><latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse reaction}}</latex></emphasis>. A special double-headed arrow ( <latex>⇌</latex>) is used to show this type of <emphasis effect="bold"><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{reversible reaction}}</latex></emphasis>:</para>
	  <para><chem_compound>XY + Z</chem_compound> <latex>⇌</latex> <chem_compound>X + YZ</chem_compound></para>
          <definition>
            <term>A reversible reaction</term>
            <meaning>
              <para>A reversible reaction is a chemical reaction that can proceed in both the forward and reverse directions. In other words, the reactants and products of the reaction may reverse roles.</para>
            </meaning>
          </definition>
	  <note type="aside">
	    <para>Remember that <latex>\to</latex> implies that A goes to B and cannot become A again. <latex>\rightleftharpoons</latex> implies that the reaction is reversible. A can go to B and B can go to A.</para>
	  </note>
          <para>So, in the following reversible reaction:</para>
	  <para><latex display="block">\overset{\textcolor{orange}{\textbf{forward }\longrightarrow}}{\textcolor{blue}{{\text{H}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}}}} {\textcolor{blue}{⇌}} {\underset{\textcolor{purple}{\longleftarrow\textbf{ reverse}}}{\textcolor{blue}{\text{2HI(g)}}}}</latex></para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{orange}{{\text{H}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} \to {\text{2HI(g)}}}\phantom{\rule{4.pt}{0ex}}</latex> is the <emphasis effect="italics"><latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward}}</latex></emphasis> reaction.</para>
	  <para>The forward reaction is always taken from the given equation and written: <emphasis effect="bold">left</emphasis> to <emphasis effect="bold">right</emphasis>.</para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{purple}{{\text{2HI(g)}} \to {\text{H}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}}}\phantom{\rule{4.pt}{0ex}}</latex> is the <emphasis effect="italics"><latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse}}</latex></emphasis> reaction.</para>
	  <para>The reverse reaction is always taken from the given equation and written: <emphasis effect="bold">right</emphasis> to <emphasis effect="bold">left</emphasis>.</para>
	<exercises>
	  <title>Chemical equilibrium</title>
	  <multi-part>
	    <shortcode>Shortcode</shortcode>
	    <header>
	      <para>Which of the following situations describes a closed system?</para>
	    </header>
	    <entry>
	      <problem>
	      <list list-type="enumerated">
		<item>
		  <para>A pot of water (without a lid) heated to <unit_number><number>80</number><unit>°C</unit></unit_number></para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para>A pot of water (with a lid) heated to <unit_number><number>80</number><unit>°C</unit></unit_number></para>
		</item>
	      </list>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para>The water is being heated, therefore there is water in the liquid and the gas phase. The water vapour can leave the pot (system) if there is no lid.</para>
	      <para><correct>ii) </correct> A closed pot of water (with a lid) heated to <unit_number><number>80</number><unit>°C</unit></unit_number></para>
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	  <entry>
	    <problem>
	      <list list-type="enumerated">
		<item>
		  <para><chem_compound>NaCl(aq) + AgNO_{3}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>NaNO_{3}(aq) + AlCl(s)</chem_compound></para>
		  <para>in an open container.</para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para><chem_compound>2CO(g) + MoO_{2}(s)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>2CO_{2}(g) + Mo(s)</chem_compound></para>
		  <para>in an open container.</para>
		</item>
	      </list>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para>Assume that none of the solid or liquid reactants or products go into the gas phase.</para>
	      <para><correct>i) </correct> <chem_compound>NaCl(aq) + AgNO_{3}(aq)</chem_compound> <latex>\to</latex> <chem_compound>NaNO_{3}(aq) + AlCl(s)</chem_compound></para>
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	</multi-part>
	<multi-part>
	  <shortcode>Shortcode</shortcode>
	  <header>
	    <para>For the reaction: <chem_compound>A + B</chem_compound> <latex>\rightleftharpoons</latex> <chem_compound>C + D</chem_compound></para>
	  </header>
	  <entry>
	    <problem>
	      <para>Write down the forward reaction</para>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para><correct><chem_compound>A + B</chem_compound> <latex>\rightarrow</latex> <chem_compound>C + D</chem_compound></correct></para>
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	  <entry>
	    <problem>
	      <para>Write down the reverse reaction</para>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para><correct><chem_compound>C + D</chem_compound> <latex>\rightarrow</latex> <chem_compound>A + B</chem_compound></correct></para>
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	  <entry>
	    <problem>
	      <para>This reaction is said to be ....... (fill in the missing word)</para>
	    </problem>
	    <solution>
	      <para>This reaction is said to be <correct>reversible</correct></para>
	    </solution>
	  </entry>
	</multi-part>
      </exercises>
        </section>
        <section type="subsection">
          <title>Dynamic equilibrium</title>
          <shortcode>ESCAY</shortcode>
	  <para>We will use the same reversible reaction that we used in an earlier example:</para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{H}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} \rightleftharpoons {\text{2HI(g)}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>The <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward}}</latex> reaction is: <latex>\phantom{\rule{4.pt}{0ex}}\textcolor{orange}{\text{H}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} \to {\text{2HI(g)}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>The <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse}}</latex> reaction is: <latex>\phantom{\rule{4.pt}{0ex}}\textcolor{purple}{\text{2HI(g)} \to {\text{H}}_{2}{\text{(g)}} + {\text{I}}_{2}{\text{(g)}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>When the rate of the forward reaction and the rate of the reverse reaction are equal, the system is said to be in <emphasis effect="bold"><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{equilibrium}}</latex></emphasis>. Figure <link target-id="fig:chemequil:equilibrium"/> shows this. Initially (time = <number>0</number>), the rate of the <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward reaction}}</latex> is high (fast). With time, the rate of the <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward reaction decreases}}</latex>. As the reaction gets closer to equilibrium the rate of decrease levels out until the forward reaction has a constant rate.</para>
	  <para>Initially the rate of the <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse reaction}}</latex> is low (slow). As the reaction proceeds with time, the rate of the <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse reaction increases}}</latex>. As the reaction progresses the rate of increase levels out until the reverse reaction has a constant rate.</para>
	  <para>At this point the forward and reverse reaction rates are equal and this is called <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\textbf{equilibrium}}</latex>.</para>
	  <figure id="fig:chemequil:equilibrium">
            <type>figure</type>
            <pspicture>
              <code>
		(-0.6,-0.6)(7.2,5.7)
		\SpecialCoor
		\pcline{-&gt;}(0,0)(0,5.5)
		\aput{:U}{Rate of Reaction}
		\pcline{-&gt;}(0,0)(7,0)
		\bput{:U}{Time}
		\uput[u](5,2.5){\blue equilibrium}
		\pscurve[linecolor=orange,showpoints=false,curvature=1 1 1](0,5)(1,3.5)(3,2.5)
		\pscurve[linecolor=purple,showpoints=false,curvature=1 1 1](0,0)(1,1.5)(3,2.5)
		\psline[linecolor=blue](3,2.5)(7,2.5)
		\newrgbcolor{purple}{0.7 0.13 0.96}
		\newrgbcolor{orange}{1 0.55 0}
		\uput[r](1,1){\purple{2HI$ \rightarrow $H$_{2}$+I$_{2}$ \textbf{(reverse)}}}
		\uput[r](1,4){\orange{H$_{2}$+I$_{2} \rightarrow $2HI \textbf{(forward)}}}
              </code>
            </pspicture>
            <caption>
	      <para>The change in rate of <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{forward}}</latex> and <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{reverse}}</latex> reactions in a closed system.</para>
            </caption>
          </figure>
	  <para>Although it is not always possible to observe any macroscopic changes, this does not mean that the reaction has stopped. The forward and reverse reactions continue to take place and so microscopic changes still occur in the system. This state is called <emphasis effect="bold">dynamic equilibrium</emphasis>.</para>
	  <definition>
	    <term>Dynamic equilibrium</term>
	    <meaning>
	      <para>There is a dynamic equilibrium in a reversible reaction when the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction. The amounts of reactants and products remain constant.</para>
	    </meaning>
	  </definition>
	  <para>In the liquid-gas phase equilibrium demonstration, dynamic equilibrium was reached when there was no observable change in the level of the water in the second beaker even though evaporation and condensation continued to take place.</para>
	  <para>For more information on dynamic equilibriums watch this video:</para>
	  <video>
	    <title>Dynamic and chemical equilibrium</title>
	    <shortcode>Shortcode 2</shortcode>
	    <url>http://www.youtube.com/embed/yFqYrBxbURY</url>
	    <width>300</width>
	    <height>245</height>
	  </video>
	</section>
      </section>
      <section type="section">
        <title>The equilibrium constant</title>
        <shortcode>ESCAZ</shortcode>
	  <para>Consider the reversible chemical reaction:</para>
	  <para><latex display="block">{\text{a}}\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}} + {\text{b}}\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}} ⇌ {\text{c}}\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}} + {\text{d}}\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}</latex></para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}}</latex> and <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}}</latex> are the reactants, <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}}</latex> and <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}</latex> are the products and a, b, c, and d are the coefficients from the balanced reaction.</para>	  
	  <para>When the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction, the system is in chemical equilibrium. It is useful to know how much of each substance is in the container - in particular the amount of products compared to the amount of reactants. A simple ratio from the balanced chemical equation gives us a number called the equilibrium constant (<chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>).</para>
	  <note type="aside">
	      <para>The subscript <emphasis effect="italics">c</emphasis> refers to the concentration of all the substances at equilibrium.</para>
	    </note>
	  <para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}} = \dfrac{{\text{[\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}}\text]}}^{c}{\text{[\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}\text]}}^{d}}{{\text{[\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}}\text]}}^{a}{\text{[\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}}\text]}}^{b}}</latex></para>
	  <note type="aside">
	    <para>The equation for the equilibrium constant uses the concentrations of the reactants and products. Square brackets mean the concentration of the compound written within the square brackets: <emphasis effect="bold">[</emphasis>x<emphasis effect="bold">]</emphasis> means the concentration of x.</para>
	  </note>
	  <para><latex>[\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}}\text], [\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}}\text], [\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}}\text] \text{and} [\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}\text]</latex> are the molar concentrations of each substance present at equilibrium.</para>
	  <definition>
	    <term>The equilibrium constant</term>
	    <meaning>
	      <para>The equilibrium constant (<chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>) is the ratio between the concentration of products and reactants in a chemical reaction.</para>
	    </meaning>
	  </definition>
	  <para>When the concentration of the reactants is much larger than the concentration of the products <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> will be small (normally less than one). When the concentration of the reactants is much less than that of the products <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> will be large (normally greater than one).</para>
	  <para>For example:</para>
	  <para><latex>2\textcolor{orange}{\text{NO}{\text{(g)}}} + 2\textcolor{orange}{\text{H}_{2}{\text{(g)}}} \rightleftharpoons \textcolor{purple}{\text{N}_{2}{\text{(g)}}} + 2\textcolor{purple}{\text{H}_{2}{\text{O(g)}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>The <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\textbf{reactants}}</latex> are <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{NO}}</latex> and <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{H}_{2}}</latex>. The <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\textbf{products}}</latex> are <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{N}_{2}}</latex> and <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{H}_{2}{\text{O}}}</latex>.</para>
	  <para>It is important to look at the coefficients of the equation as well:</para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{orange}{\textbf{2}}</latex><chem_compound>NO(g)</chem_compound> + <latex>\textcolor{orange}{\textbf{2}}</latex><chem_compound>H_{2}(g)</chem_compound> <latex>\rightleftharpoons \textcolor{purple}{\textbf{1}}</latex><chem_compound>N_{2}(g)</chem_compound> + <latex>\textcolor{purple}{\textbf{2}}</latex><chem_compound>H_{2}O(g)</chem_compound></para>
	  <para><chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> for this equation will therefore be written as follows:</para>
	  <para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{[N}_{2}{\text{]}}{\textcolor{purple}{^{1}}}{\text{[H}}_{2}{\text{O]}}{\textcolor{purple}{^{2}}}}{\text{[NO]}{\textcolor{orange}{^{2}}}{\text{[H}}_{2}{\text{]}}{\textcolor{orange}{^{2}}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>In the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> the concentration of a product or reactant is taken to the power of its coefficient in the balanced reaction. So if the coefficient of a product (C) is 3 in the balanced equation, then the concentration of C ([C]) will be written <chem_compound>[C]^{3}</chem_compound> in the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>.</para>
	  <para>We leave out reactants or products that are either pure <emphasis effect="bold">liquids</emphasis> or in the <emphasis effect="bold">solid</emphasis> phase when calculating <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>. For example:</para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{C(s)}}</latex> <chem_compound>+ H_{2}O(g)</chem_compound> <latex>⇌</latex> <chem_compound>CO(g) + H_{2}(g)</chem_compound><latex>{\phantom{\rule{40.pt}{0ex}}}\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{{\text{[CO][H}}_{2}\text{]}}{{\text{[H}}_{2}\text{O]}}</latex></para>
	  <section type="subsection">
	    <title>Calculating the equilibrium constant</title>
	    <shortcode>ESCBA</shortcode>
	    <para>When calculations involving the equilibrium constant are done, the following tips may help:</para>
	    <list list-type="enumerated">
	      <item>
		<para>Always <emphasis effect="italics">read the question carefully</emphasis> to be sure that you understand what you have been asked to calculate.</para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para>If the equilibrium constant is involved, make sure that the concentrations you use are the concentrations <emphasis effect="bold">at equilibrium</emphasis>, and not the concentrations or quantities that are present at some other time in the reaction.</para>
	      </item>
	      <item>
		<para>When you are doing more complicated calculations, it helps to draw up a RICE table (Table <link target-id="tab:chemicalequilibrium:RICEtable"/>). This is gone into in more detail later in this section.</para>
	      </item>
	    </list>
	    <para>Remember that the general form of the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> of a reaction at chemical equilibrium (a<latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}}</latex> + b<latex>\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}}</latex> <latex>⇌</latex> c<latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}}</latex> + d<latex>\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}</latex>) is:</para>
	    <para><latex display="block">{K}_{c}=\dfrac{{\text{[\textcolor{purple}{\text{C}}\text]}}^{c}{\text{[\textcolor{purple}{\text{D}}\text]}}^{d}}{{\text{[\textcolor{orange}{\text{A}}\text]}}^{a}{\text{[\textcolor{orange}{\text{B}}\text]}}^{b}}</latex></para>
	    <worked_example>
	      <title>Writing expressions for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound></title>
	      <question>
		<para>For the reaction:</para>
		<para><chem_compound>9X(g) + Y_{3}(g)</chem_compound> <latex>\rightleftharpoons</latex> <chem_compound>3X_{3}Y(g)</chem_compound></para>
		<para>Write an expression for the equilibrium constant <chem_compound>{K}_{c}</chem_compound>.</para>
	      </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Write the general expression for <chem_compound>{K}_{c}</chem_compound></title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{[C]}^{c}{\text{[D]}}^{d}}{\text{[A]}^{a}{\text{[B]}}^{b}}</latex></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Determine the reactants and the products of the reaction</title>
		<para>X(g) and <chem_compound>Y_{3}(g)</chem_compound> are both reactants. They are gases and will be included in the expression.</para>
		<para><chem_compound>X_{3}Y(g)</chem_compound> is a product. It is a gas and will be included in the expression.</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Write the general expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> for this reaction</title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{[X}_{3}{\text{Y]}}^{z}}{\text{[X]}^{x}{\text{[Y}}_{3}{\text{]}}^{y}}</latex></para>
              </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>What are the coefficients in the balanced equation?</title>
		<para>The compound <chem_compound>X</chem_compound> has a coefficient of <emphasis effect="bold">9</emphasis>. The compound <chem_compound>Y_{3}</chem_compound> has a coefficient of <emphasis effect="bold">1</emphasis>. The compound <chem_compound>X_{3}Y</chem_compound> has a coefficient of <emphasis effect="bold">3</emphasis>.</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Write the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> for this reaction</title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{[X}_{3}{\text{Y]}}^{3}}{\text{[X]}^{9}{\text{[Y}}_{3}{\text{]}}^{1}}</latex></para>
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
          <worked_example>
            <title>Calculating reagent concentration</title>
            <question>
              <para>For the reaction:</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>S(s) + O_{2}(g)</chem_compound> <latex>⇌</latex> <chem_compound>SO_{2}(g)</chem_compound></para>
                <list list-type="enumerated">
                  <item>
                    <para>Write an expression for the equilibrium constant.</para>
                  </item>
                  <item>
		    <para>Calculate the equilibrium concentration of <chem_compound>O_{2}</chem_compound> if:</para>
		    <para><chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> = 6 and <chem_compound>[SO_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>3</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> at equilibrium.</para>
                  </item>
                </list>           
            </question>
            <answer>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Determine which compounds will be part of the <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> expression</title>
		<para><latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{S(s)}}</latex> + <chem_compound>O_{2}(g)</chem_compound> <latex>⇌</latex> <chem_compound>SO_{2}(g)</chem_compound></para>
		<para><chem_compound>O_{2}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>SO_{2}</chem_compound> are gases and so will be part of the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>. S is solid and so will not be part of the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>.</para>
	      </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Write the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound></title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\frac{{\text{[SO}}_{2}\text{]}}{{\text{[O}}_{2}\text{]}}</latex></para>		
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Re-arrange the expression so that oxygen is on its own on one side of the expression</title>
                <latex display="block">{\text{[{O}}_{2}\text{]}}=\frac{{\text{[SO}}_{2}\text{]}}{\text{K}_{\text{c}}}</latex>             
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Fill in the values you know and calculate <chem_compound>[O_{2}]</chem_compound> </title>
		<latex display="block">{\text{[O}}_{2}\text{]}=\frac{<unit_number><number>3</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>}{6} = <unit_number><number>0.5</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></latex>               
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
	  <worked_example>
            <title>Calculating <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound></title>
            <question>
              <para>For the reaction:</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>SO_{2}(g) + NO_{2}(g)</chem_compound> <latex>\rightleftharpoons</latex> <chem_compound>NO(g) + SO_{3}(g)</chem_compound></para>
	      <para>The concentrations of the compounds used are:</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>[SO_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>, <chem_compound>[NO_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.1</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>, <chem_compound>[NO]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.4</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number> and</para>
	      <para><chem_compound>[SO_{3}] </chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.2</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
              <para>Calculate the value of <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>.</para>
            </question>
            <answer>
              <workstep>
                <title>Write the general expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound></title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{[C]}^{c}{\text{[D]}}^{d}}{\text{[A]}^{a}{\text{[B]}}^{b}}</latex></para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Determine the reactants and the products of the reaction</title>
		<para><chem_compound>SO_{2}(g)</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>NO_{2}(g)</chem_compound> are both reactants. They are gases and will be included in the expression.</para>
		<para><chem_compound>NO(g)</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>SO_{3}(g)</chem_compound> are both products. They are gases and will be included in the expression.</para>
	      </workstep>
	      <workstep>
		<title>Write the expression for <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> for this reaction</title>
		<para>All four compounds have a coefficient of <emphasis effect="bold">1</emphasis>.</para>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\frac{{\text{[NO]}}^{1}{\text{[SO}}_{3}\text{]}^{1}}{{\text{[SO}}_{2}{\text{]}}^{1}{\text{[NO}}_{2}\text{]}^{1}}</latex></para>
              </workstep>
              <workstep>
                <title>Fill in the values you know for this expression and calculate <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound></title>
		<para><latex display="block">\text{K}_{\text{c}}=\dfrac{\text{(}<number>0.4</number>\text{)(}<number>0.2</number>\text{)}}{\text{(}<number>0.2</number>\text{)(}<number>0.1</number>\text{)}}= <number>4</number></latex></para>
              </workstep>
            </answer>
          </worked_example>
	  <note type="tip">
	    <para>You do not need to fill in the coefficients in a <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> calculation when they are <number>1</number>. They are shown here so that you do not forget where the coefficients are reflected in the equation.</para>
	  </note>
	  <para>When you are doing more complicated calculations, it helps to draw up a RICE table (Table <link target-id="tab:chemicalequilibrium:RICEtable"/>). A RICE table is an easy way of organising information in equilibrium calculations.</para>
