	<section type="subsection">
	  <title>The effect of pressure on equilibrium</title>
          <shortcode>ESCBF</shortcode>
	  <para>If the pressure of a gaseous reaction mixture is changed the equilibrium will shift to minimise that change.</para>
	  <list list-type="bulleted">
	    <item>
	      <para>If the pressure is <emphasis effect="bold">increased</emphasis> the equilibrium will shift to favour a <emphasis effect="bold">decrease</emphasis> in pressure.</para>
	    </item>
	    <item>
	      <para>If the pressure is <emphasis effect="bold">decreased</emphasis> the equilibrium will shift to favour an <emphasis effect="bold">increase</emphasis> in pressure.</para>
	    </item>
	  </list>
	  <para>When the volume of a system is decreased (and the temperature is constant), the pressure will increase. There are more collisions with the walls of the container. If there are fewer gas molecules there will be fewer collisions, and therefore lower pressure. The equilibrium will shift in a direction that reduces the number of gas molecules so that the pressure is also reduced. So, to predict in which direction the equilibrium will shift to change pressure you need to <latex>\textcolor{darkgreen}{\text{look at the number of gas molecules in the balanced}}</latex> <latex>\textcolor{darkgreen}{\text{reactions}}</latex>.</para>
	  <note type="tip">
	    <para>Remember from <link url="todo">Grade 11</link> that:</para>
	    <para><latex display="block">\text{p} \propto \dfrac{\text{T}}{\text{V}}</latex></para>
	    <para>That is, if the temperature remains constant, and the volume is increased, the pressure will decrease.</para>
	    <pspicture>
	      <code>
		(-0.35,-0.1)(2.5,3.1)
		\psframe(0,2)(1,3)
		\rput(2,2.7){low V}
		\rput(2,2.3){high p}
		\psframe(-0.25,0)(1.25,1.5)
		\rput(2,0.95){high V}
		\rput(2,0.55){low p}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](0,1){0.1}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](0.5,0.5){0.1}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](1,1.3){0.1}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](0.3,2.2){0.1}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](0.5,2.8){0.1}
		\pscircle[linecolor=red,fillstyle=solid,fillcolor=red](0.7,2.6){0.1}
	      </code>
	    </pspicture>
	    <para>Figure <link target-id="fig:chemicalequilibrium:pressure"/> shows a decrease in pressure by an increase in the volume, and an increase in pressure by a decrease in the volume.</para>
	  </note>
	  <para>For example, the equation for the reaction between nitrogen and hydrogen is shown below:</para>
	  <para><latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{N}_{2}\text{(g)}} + \textcolor{blue}{\text{3H}_{2}\text{(g)}} ⇌ \textcolor{red}{\text{2NH}_{3}\text{(g)}}</latex></para>
	  <para>The ratio in the balanced equation is <chem_compound>1:3:2</chem_compound>. That is, for every <unit_number><number>1</number><unit>molecule</unit></unit_number> of <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{N}_{2}\text{ gas}}</latex> there are <unit_number><number>3</number><unit>molecules</unit></unit_number> of <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\text{H}_{2}\text{ gas}}</latex> and <unit_number><number>2</number><unit>molecules</unit></unit_number> of <latex>\textcolor{red}{\text{NH}_{3}\text{ gas}}</latex> (from the balanced equation). Therefore the ratio is <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\textbf{4 molecules of reactant gas}}</latex> to <latex>\textcolor{red}{\textbf{2 molecules of product gas}}</latex>.</para>
	  <list list-type="bulleted">
	    <item>
	      <para>An <emphasis effect="bold">increase</emphasis> in pressure will:</para>
	      <list list-type="bulleted">
		<item>
		  <para>Favour the reaction that <emphasis effect="bold">decreases</emphasis> the number of gas molecules.</para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para>There are <latex>\textcolor{red}{\textbf{fewer molecules of product gas}}</latex> than reactant gas, so the <emphasis effect="bold">forward reaction</emphasis> is favoured.</para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para>The equilibrium will <emphasis effect="bold">shift to the right</emphasis> and the <emphasis effect="bold">yield</emphasis> of <latex>\textcolor{red}{\textbf{NH}_{3}}</latex> will <emphasis effect="bold">increase</emphasis>.</para>
		</item>
	      </list>
	    </item>
	    <item>
	      <para>A <emphasis effect="bold">decrease</emphasis> in pressure will:</para>
	      <list list-type="bulleted">
		<item>
		  <para>Favour the reaction that <emphasis effect="bold">increases</emphasis> the number of gas molecules.</para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para>There are <latex>\textcolor{blue}{\textbf{more molecules of reactant gas}}</latex>, so the <emphasis effect="bold">reverse reaction</emphasis> is favoured.</para>
		</item>
		<item>
		  <para>The equilibrium will <emphasis effect="bold">shift to the left</emphasis> and the <emphasis effect="bold">yield</emphasis> of <latex>\textcolor{red}{\textbf{NH}_{3}}</latex> will <emphasis effect="bold">decrease</emphasis>.</para>
		</item>
	      </list>
	    </item>
	  </list>
	  <para>Consider illustration in Figure <link target-id="fig:chemicalequilibrium:pressure"/>.</para>
	  <figure id="fig:chemicalequilibrium:pressure">
	    <type>figure</type>
	    <pspicture style:width="0.8">
