	  <para>Figure <link target-id="fig:chemicalequilibrium:pressure"/> shows how changing the pressure of a system results in a shift in the equilibrium to counter that change. In the original system there are <emphasis effect="bold">12</emphasis> molecules in total: <latex>\newrgbcolor{skyblue}{0.33 0.41 1}{\textcolor{skyblue}{6{\text {H}}_{2}}} + {\textcolor{blue}{2{\text{N}}_{2}}} ⇌ {\textcolor{red}{4{\text{NH}}_{3}}}</latex></para>
	  <para>If you <emphasis effect="bold">decrease</emphasis> the pressure (shown by an increase in volume), the equilibrium will shift to <emphasis effect="bold">increase</emphasis> the number of gas molecules. That shift is to the left and the number of <chem_compound>H_{2}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>N_{2}</chem_compound> molecules will increase while the number of <chem_compound>NH_{3}</chem_compound> molecules will decrease:</para> 
	  <pspicture>
	    <code>
	      (-0.6,-0.5)(13,0.5)
	      \newrgbcolor{skyblue}{0.33 0.41 1}
	      \rput(-0.3,0){\textbf{(a)}}
