		<para><emphasis effect="bold">Concentration-time and mole-time graphs</emphasis></para>
		<list list-type="bulleted">
		  <item>
		    <para><emphasis effect="bold">A change in concentration</emphasis> of a substance would appear as a sharp increase or decrease in the concentration or number of moles of that substance and a gradual change in the other substances.</para>
		  </item>
		  <item>
		    <para><emphasis effect="bold">A change in temperature</emphasis> would affect both the forward and reverse reactions. However, one reaction would be affected more than the other. So the reactants and products would be affected gradually, in the opposite direction (one increased, the other decreased).</para>
		  </item>
		  <item>
		    <para><emphasis effect="bold">A change in pressure</emphasis> of the reaction would cause a sharp increase or decrease in all the reactants and products. For an increase in pressure, if the forward reaction is then favoured the reactant concentrations will decrease, and if the reverse reaction is then favoured the product concentrations will decrease.</para>
		  </item>
		  <item>
		    <para><emphasis effect="bold">The addition of a catalyst</emphasis> would increase both the forward and reverse reaction rates, meaning the equilibrium is reached faster. So if the reaction is already at equilibrium there will be no effect on a concentration-time or moles-time graph.</para>
		  </item>
		</list>
