		    <workstep>
		      <title>How much time was necessary for the system to reach equilibrium?</title>
		      
		      <para>The concentration of all three compounds becomes constant at t = <unit_number><number>15</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>. This means that the reaction has reached equilibrium.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>How can you determine which rate is faster from the concentration graphs?</title>
		      
		      <para>If the concentrations of the reactants (<chem_compound>CO</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>Cl_{2}</chem_compound>) are steadily decreasing or the concentration of the product (<chem_compound>COCl_{2}</chem_compound>) is increasing then the forward reaction is faster than the reverse reaction.</para>
		      <para>Similarly, if the concentrations of the reactants (<chem_compound>CO</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>Cl_{2}</chem_compound>) are steadily increasing or the concentration of the product (<chem_compound>COCl_{2}</chem_compound>) is decreasing then the reverse reaction is faster than the forward reaction.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>Compare the forward and reverse reaction rates at t = <unit_number><number>5</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>, t = <unit_number><number>17</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> and t = <unit_number><number>23</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number></title>
		      
		      <para>At t = <unit_number><number>5</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> and at t = <unit_number><number>23</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> the concentrations of the reactants are decreasing and the concentration of the product is increasing. Therefore the rate of the forward reaction is faster than the rate of the reverse reaction.</para>
		      <para>At t = <unit_number><number>17</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> the concentrations of the reactants and products are constant (unchanging). Therefore the reaction is in equilibrium and the rate of the forward reaction equals the rate of the reverse reaction.</para>
