		  <answer>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>Check the axes so that you know what the variables are on this graph</title>
		      
		      <para>The axes are labelled concentration and time. Therefore this is a concentration-time graph.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>After how many seconds does the system reach equilibrium?</title>
		      
		      <para>The concentration of all three compounds becomes constant at t = <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>. This means that the system takes <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> to reach equilibrium.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>What are the concentrations of <chem_compound>H_{2}</chem_compound>, <chem_compound>I_{2}</chem_compound>, and <chem_compound>HI</chem_compound> at t = <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>, <unit_number><number>25</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>, and <unit_number><number>45</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>?</title>
		      
		      <para>Reading off the graph you can see that at <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><chem_compound>[H_{2}]</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>[I_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.75</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>, <chem_compound>[HI]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>6.0</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
		      <para>At <unit_number><number>25</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><chem_compound>[H_{2}]</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>[I_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>0.6</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>, <chem_compound>[HI]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>4.8</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
		      <para>At <unit_number><number>45</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><chem_compound>[H_{2}]</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>[I_{2}]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>1.5</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number>, <chem_compound>[HI]</chem_compound> = <unit_number><number>2.75</number><unit>mol.dm<sup>-3</sup></unit></unit_number></para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>Write an expression for the equilibrium constant of this reaction and calculate <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound>.</title>
		      
		      <para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{c}} = \dfrac{\text{[HI]}^{2}}{\text{[H}_{2}{\text{][I}_{2}{\text{]}}}}</latex></para>
		      <para>At t = <unit_number><number>10</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{c}} = \dfrac{<number>6.0</number>^{2}}{(<number>0.75</number>)(<number>0.75</number>)} = </latex> <number>64.0</number></para>
		      <para>At t = <unit_number><number>25</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{c}} = \dfrac{<number>4.8</number>^{2}}{(<number>0.6</number>)(<number>0.6</number>)} = </latex> <number>64.0</number></para>
		      <para>At t = <unit_number><number>45</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>:</para>
		      <para><latex>\text{K}_{\text{c}} = \dfrac{<number>2.75</number>^{2}}{(<number>1.5</number>)(<number>1.5</number>)} = </latex> <number>3.4</number></para>
		      <para>The different <chem_compound>K_{c}</chem_compound> at <unit_number><number>45</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> means that the event at t = <unit_number><number>35</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> must be a change in temperature.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>Explain what happened at t = <unit_number><number>20</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number>?</title>
		      
		      <para>The concentration of <chem_compound>HI</chem_compound> decreases sharply, as a result there is a slight decrease in the concentration of <chem_compound>H_{2}</chem_compound> and <chem_compound>I_{2}</chem_compound>. Therefore <chem_compound>HI</chem_compound> must have been removed from the system.</para>
		      <para>After this there is a shift to increase the amount of <chem_compound>HI</chem_compound>, that is in the forward direction.</para>
		    </workstep>
		    <workstep>
		      <title>If the change at t = <unit_number><number>35</number><unit>s</unit></unit_number> is due to an increase in temperature, is the reaction exothermic or endothermic? Explain your answer.</title>
		      
		      <para>An increase in temperature caused the concentration of the product to decrease and the concentrations of the reactants to increase. This means that the reverse reaction has been favoured.</para>
		      <para>An increase in temperature will favour the reaction that takes heat in and cools the reaction vessel (endothermic). Therefore the reverse reaction must be endothermic and the forward reaction must be exothermic. The reaction is exothermic.</para>
		    </workstep>
		  </answer>
